df <- rio::import(
"https://github.com/fivethirtyeight/data/raw/master/alcohol-consumption/drinks.csv")
consume_hist <- ggplot(
  df,
  aes(
    total_litres_of_pure_alcohol)
  ) +
  geom_histogram(
    fill = "#56B4E9",
    color = "white",
    alpha = 0.9,
    bins = 15) + # bins = 5, bins = 25
  labs(x = "Total litres of pure alcohol",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()
consume_hist

At bins = 5, the bin width was too large, smaller features in the distribution of the data disappear. At bins = 25, the bin width is too small, the histogram became overly peaky and visually busy and the main trend in the data was obscured.

consume_dens <- ggplot(
  df,
  aes(total_litres_of_pure_alcohol)
  ) +
  geom_density(
    fill = "#56B4E9",
    bw = 1) + # bw = .5, bw = 1.5
  labs(x = "Total litres of pure alcohol",
       y = "Density") +
  theme_minimal()
consume_dens

At bw = .5, the bandwidth is too large, the smaller features in the distribution of the data disappear. At bw = 1.5, the bandwidth is too small, the density estimate became overly peaky and visually busy and the main trends in the data were obscured.

df2 <- df %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = ends_with("_servings"),
    names_to = "type",
    values_to = "servings")
alcohol_dr <- ggplot(
  df2,
  aes(
    servings,
    type,
    height = ..density..)
  ) +
  # coord_cartesian(xlim = c(1, 400)) +
  geom_density_ridges_gradient(
    scale = 1,
    fill = "#56B4E9",
    stat = "density",
    trim = TRUE) +
  labs(
    x = "Total number of servings",
    y = "Types of alcohol") +
  theme_minimal()
alcohol_dr

alcohol_od <- ggplot(
  df2,
  aes(servings)
  ) +
  geom_density(
    aes(
    fill = type),
    color = "black",
    alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  theme_minimal()
alcohol_od

alcohol_wrap <- ggplot(
  df2,
  aes(servings)
  ) +
  geom_histogram(
    aes(
      fill = type),
      alpha = 0.9,
      bins = 10) + # bins = 5, bins = 15
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  facet_wrap(~type) +
  theme_minimal()
alcohol_wrap

Double coding the density ridges graph by adding individual colors to the servings may have provided similar information (visually) as the facet wrap graphic. I found I needed to work the xlim (trim) for the density ridges graph because the x-axis extended to -100. My density ridges output seemed to be communicating negative servings.
The facet wrap visualization provides an intuitive and highly interpretable visualization of the drinks data. We clearly see that wine servings outpace other drink types, in the initial servings count. However, the scale_fill_brewer is not working as advertised.
Even though I admit to having limited data interpretation skills, and after trying several color pallets, density ridges continues to be the most difficult to interpret for me. This particular density ridges visualization appears (in my opinion) to have four variables represented.

df3 <- df2 %>%
  arrange(
    desc(total_litres_of_pure_alcohol)
    ) %>%
  slice(1:75) %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  mutate(
    total_servings = sum(servings),
    percent_servings = servings / total_servings)

stack <- ggplot(
  df3,
  aes(
    country,
    percent_servings)
  ) +
  geom_col(
    aes(
      fill = type),
      alpha = .9) +
  scale_fill_brewer(
    palette = "Paired",
    name = "Alcohol Type",
    breaks = c(
      "wine_servings",
      "spirit_servings",
      "beer_servings"),
    labels = c("Wine",
               "Spirits",
               "Beer")
    ) +
  coord_flip() +
scale_y_continuous(
  expand = c(0, 0)) +
  labs(
    y = "Proportion of total alcohol consumed",
    x = NULL,
    title = "Alcohol consumption by type",
    subtitle = "Top 25 countries displayed (according to total liters consumed)") +
  theme_minimal(
    base_size = 20) +
  theme(
    plot.title.position = "plot",
    legend.position = "bottom")
stack
